  "dimension_notes": {
    "error_consistency": {
      "evidence": [
        "`main.go` aborts only on `config.Initialize()` failure, but logs and continues on failures from `broadcast.Initialize()`, `docker.Initialize()`, `importer.Initialize()`, `system.InitializeWiFi()`, and other subsystem initializers, creating an inconsistent startup-failure contract.",
        "`docker/network/network.go` logs and suppresses container stop failures inside `KillContainerUsingPort`; the function still returns success as long as a candidate container ID is found and stop is attempted.",
        "`goseg/docker/network` then `KillContainerUsingPort` is used in startup (`lifecycle.Initialize`), so the launch can proceed after control-plane remediation steps silently failed."
      ],
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "confidence": "high"
    }
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "GS_ERR_001",
      "summary": "`KillContainerUsingPort` can report success when container stop fails, masking port-reclaim failures during startup.",
      "related_files": ["goseg/docker/network/network.go", "goseg/docker/lifecycle/lifecycle.go"],
      "evidence": [
        "`KillContainerUsingPort` iterates matching containers and on `cli.ContainerStop` error logs only (`zap.L().Error`) and does not return that error.",
        "In the same function, it returns `nil` immediately after attempting stop on first match even if stop failed.",
        "`lifecycle.Initialize` calls `network.KillContainerUsingPort(80)` and only logs the error, so upstream startup is not blocked by failed port cleanup."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Change `KillContainerUsingPort` to only return nil when all required teardown steps succeed; return the stop error when a stop attempt fails and let callers decide severity. In `lifecycle.Initialize`, fail hard or route to explicit degraded-mode recovery when port cleanup fails.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "soft_fail_control_paths"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "error_consistency",
      "identifier": "GS_ERR_002",
      "summary": "Top-level startup boundary treats subsystem initialization errors inconsistently, enabling partially initialized runtime without clear failure contract.",
      "related_files": ["goseg/main.go", "goseg/broadcast/broadcast.go"],
      "evidence": [
        "`main.go` exits on `config.Initialize()` error but only logs errors for many later initializers and continues startup.",
        "`broadcast.Initialize()` can return bootstrap errors (`unable to initialize broadcast state`) while `main.go` does not propagate these as startup failures.",
        "`main.go` starts the server and long-running routines even after non-fatal-logged failures in multiple dependencies, increasing risk of nil/partial state behavior at runtime."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Introduce a consistent init contract (fatal vs recoverable) and enforce it at the main boundary. Return/aggregate initialization errors from each subsystem, and decide deterministic policy: either stop startup on mandatory init failures or record state and suppress route/routine registration until dependency checks pass.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "root_cause_cluster": "soft_fail_control_paths"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "Missing boundary contract for failure severity (soft-fail vs hard-fail) across setup/control paths.",
      "Log-and-continue patterns without returning actionable errors in cross-module control operations."
    ],
    "likely_symptoms": [
      "GS_ERR_001",
      "GS_ERR_002"
